Freezing funding appropriated by Congress is not only a clear violation of the law, it would also have a devastating impact on NE Ohio. I will fight this at every turn until President Trump reverses course and implements federal spending as dictated by Congress.

FEMA Assistance: FEMA’s Public Assistance and certain Individual Assistance programs are paused, including crisis counseling, Other Needs Assistance, disaster unemployment, and case management services. 10/10
Job Training Programs: Adult job training grants that help workers gain skills and find employment could face cuts. This would harm job seekers and slow our economy. 9/10
Head Start & Early Head Start: Preschool services for low-income families with kids under 5 could be scaled back. These programs are critical for early childhood development. 8/10
Child Care Subsidies: The Child Care and Development Block Grant (CCDBG) helps low-income families afford care for kids under 13. Funding freezes could make it harder for parents to work. 7/10
IDEA Special Education: Freezing this funding could affect 7.5 million kids with disabilities, making it harder for them to get the support they need to succeed in school. 6/10

Title I Grants for Schools: Funding that supports children in low-income classrooms could be targeted—impacting an estimated 25 million students. Freezing these funds would widen education inequality. 5/10

LIHEAP (Heating/Cooling Assistance): Nearly 7 million low-income households rely on this program to stay warm in the winter and cool in the summer. Funding freezes could put vulnerable families at risk. 4/10

SNAP (Food Assistance): While they claim it’s exempt, SNAP is among 2,000+ programs flagged for possible freezes. This could mean administrative delays and funding cuts that harm families needing food assistance. 3/10

WIC Nutrition Benefits: Funding for pregnant women, new moms, and kids under 5 could be at risk. Millions of families depend on WIC to stay healthy, and attempts to freeze funding put them in jeopardy. 2/10
